<subSubSection id="C340F0BC9F4C611B24A1FD30FA59FC90" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE5A3379F4C611B24A1FD30FAACFD13" blockId="4.[192,1440,649,1090]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<bibRefCitation id="EFCBDEC69F4C611B24A1FD30FE51FD50" author="Rivalier, E." box="[232,413,649,673]" journalOrPublisher="Revue Francaise d'Entomologie" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="249 - 268" part="17" refId="ref5593" refString="Rivalier, E. 1950. Demembrement du genre Cicindela Linne (Travail preliminaire limite a la faune palearctique). Revue Francaise d'Entomologie 17: 249 - 268." title="Demembrement du genre Cicindela Linne (Travail preliminaire limite a la faune palearctique)" type="journal article" year="1950">Rivalier (1950)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B2657FD30FD6EFD50" box="[542,674,649,673]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Apterodela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B2657FD30FD6EFD50" box="[542,674,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Apterodela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B273EFD30FC3CFD50" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1831" box="[887,1008,649,673]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cylindera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B273EFD30FC3CFD50" box="[887,1008,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cylindera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and designated 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B20FEFD33FF37FD33" authority="Bates, 1883" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1883" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cylindera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovipennis">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B20FEFD33FB06FD50" box="[1207,1226,650,673]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B2091FD33FA80FD50" box="[1240,1356,650,673]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">ovipennis</emphasis>
Bates, 1883
</taxonomicName>
as the type. Given the polyphyly of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B26FDFD10FCE1FD30" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1831" box="[692,813,681,705]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cylindera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B26FDFD10FCE1FD30" box="[692,813,681,705]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cylindera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFCBDEC69F4C611B2774FD10FBD5FD33" author="Gough, H. M. &amp; D. P. Duran &amp; A. Y. Kawahara &amp; E. F. Toussaint" box="[829,1049,681,706]" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="305 - 321" part="44" refId="ref5110" refString="Gough, H. M., D. P. Duran, A. Y. Kawahara, and E. F. Toussaint. 2019. A comprehensive molecular phylogeny of tiger beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Cicindelinae). Systematic Entomology 44: 305 - 321." title="A comprehensive molecular phylogeny of tiger beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Cicindelinae)" type="journal article" year="2019">Gough et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
; this study) and a monophyletic and morphologically distinct 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B266DFD70FC4EFD13" authority="(Sota et al. 2011)" authorityName="Sota" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Sota" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[548,898,713,738]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Apterodela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B266DFD70FD64FD10" box="[548,680,713,737]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Apterodela</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFCBDEC69F4C611B26FEFD73FCB5FD13" author="Sota, T. &amp; H. Liang &amp; Y. Enokido &amp; M. Hori" box="[695,889,713,738]" journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="715 - 727" part="102" refId="ref5846" refString="Sota, T., H. Liang, Y. Enokido, and M. Hori. 2011. Phylogeny and divergence time of island tiger beetles of the genus Cylindera (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae) in East Asia. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 102: 715 - 727." title="Phylogeny and divergence time of island tiger beetles of the genus Cylindera (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae) in East Asia" type="journal article" year="2011">Sota et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, we recognize the clade as a full genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE5A3379F4C611B24A1FD50FA59FC90" blockId="4.[192,1440,649,1090]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The Nearctic species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B25A6FD50FD69FCF0" authorityName="Duran &amp; Gough" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[495,677,745,769]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Apterodela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unipunctata">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B25A6FD50FD69FCF0" box="[495,677,745,769]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">A. unipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is strongly supported (Bootstrap = 98) as sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B2145FD50FA6CFCF0" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1883" box="[1292,1440,745,769]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Cylindera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovipennis">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B2145FD50FAD3FCF1" box="[1292,1311,745,768]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B2165FD53FA6CFCF0" box="[1324,1440,746,769]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">ovipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in our phylogeny (
<figureCitation id="1361BFB29F4C611B25E9FCB0FE28FCD3" box="[416,484,777,802]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[192,275,1790,1812]" captionTargetBox="[195,1449,881,1762]" captionTargetId="graphics@2.[195,1449,878,1764]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Maximum-likelihood phylogenetic hypothesis for North American lineages Ellipsoptera, Dromochorus, Brasiella, and Cylindera. Maximum-likelihood phylogeny inferred in IQ-TREE based on three mitochondrial fragments (16S, COX3 and CytB). Taxon naming follows previous naming conventions with different colors highlighting new generic groupings we propose. * denotes the C. lemniscata specimen from GenBank and † denotes the chimera specimen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468261/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) and is remarkably similar in morphology to species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B20DCFCB0FAD5FCD0" box="[1173,1305,777,801]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Apterodela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B20DCFCB0FAD5FCD0" box="[1173,1305,777,801]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Apterodela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Asia. Like the other members of the genus, it is large (14–18 mm), with a coarsely striated concave frons, flattened ovate elytra with reduced maculations, dark infuscations and prominent subsutural foveae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C340F0BC9F4C611B24A1FCD0FD94FBB3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BE5A3379F4C611B24A1FCD0FD94FBB3" blockId="4.[192,1440,649,1090]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Ecologically, 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B25C2FCD0FD88FC70" authorityName="Duran &amp; Gough" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[395,580,873,897]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Apterodela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unipunctata">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B25C2FCD0FE52FC71" box="[395,414,873,896]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B25E7FCD3FD88FC70" box="[430,580,874,897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">unipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unlike any other species of Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B207DFCD0FB71FC70" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1076,1213,873,897]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Cicindelini">Cicindelini</taxonomicName>
. Adult beetles are typically found when they cross forest trails and openings, but they also frequent darker closed-canopy forested areas where they may hunt in or on the leaf litter. The first author has collected beetles in dense late-succession oak forest in areas that were over 100m from a trail or opening. It is quite likely that most casual observations of this species are biased towards edges, as it is more likely to be seen when crossing trails and light gaps. Asian 
<taxonomicName id="4C5AD8B49F4C611B26C3FBB0FCC2FBD0" box="[650,782,1033,1057]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Apterodela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B92E7F259F4C611B26C3FBB0FCC2FBD0" box="[650,782,1033,1057]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Apterodela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species share similar forest-dwelling natural history and affinity for leaf litter (
<figureCitation id="1361BFB29F4C611B264BFB90FD85FBB3" box="[514,585,1065,1090]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="4.[192,275,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,1139,1843]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[192,1440,1139,1843]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 3. In situ photographs of Apterodela spp. A) Apterodela ovipennis (Asia). B) Apterodela unipunctata (North America)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468265" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468265/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
